# Services and Repositories

## Workflow Naming

One business operation = one service file:

```
RegisterAssetService
AllocateAssetService
CreateBookingService
ApproveMaintenanceService
CloseAuditService
```

Not `AssetService` or `MaintenanceService`.

## Repository Rule

Every module gets **one repository from day one**. Keep it small:

```typescript
interface AssetRepository {
  create(data: CreateAssetData): Promise<Asset>;
  findById(id: string): Promise<Asset | null>;
  findBySerial(serial: string): Promise<Asset | null>;
  updateStatus(id: string, status: AssetStatus): Promise<Asset>;
}
```

No generic repository. No base repository. Prisma stays inside repository implementations.

## Service Responsibilities

| Layer | Owns |
|-------|------|
| Service | Workflow orchestration, business rules, transaction boundary, side effects |
| Repository | Data access only |

## Idempotency

Every mutation service must answer: **if this request is repeated, what happens?**

| Action | Repeated response |
|--------|-------------------|
| Allocate | Already allocated (409) |
| Return | Already returned (409) |
| Approve | Already approved (success or 409) |
| Close audit | Already closed (409) |

## Concurrency Documentation

Each workflow documents: race condition, transaction, DB constraint, failure response (HTTP code).
